<TITLE> US calls for restraint after Georgia election </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TBILISI, Jan 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The United States on Sunday urged Georgians to show restraint and respect an upcoming Western monitoring report on the country's presidential election after the opposition said the vote was rigged and called for protests. Georgian leader Mikhail Saakashvili, a staunch US ally, called the snap election in November after using police to crush opposition protests. An exit poll showed Saakashvili gaining over half the votes, around double that of his nearest challenger, who later said the Georgian leader had cheated and that the opposition had won. But Washington's top emissary to the region, Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Matthew Bryza, urged calm. "If the experts determine that the election was not rigged then there is absolutely no justification, and it would be absolutely undemocratic, to claim otherwise," Bryza told Reuters in a telephone interview from Washington. "How unfortunate that would be for Georgian democracy." Western monitors are expected to give their assessment of the election at around 3 p.m. (1100 GMT). Levan Gachechiladze, leader of a nine-party opposition coalition, on Saturday said ballots had been stuffed, voters intimidated and the results rigged by Saakashvili and he called supporters to rally at 2 p.m. in Tbilisi. Reuters reporters saw a police water cannon and around six buses of uniformed men driving into Tbilisi on Sunday morning. "I would hope very much that there would be no use of force whatsoever. The government has a responsibility, of course, to maintain the security of the country but protesters also have a right to demonstrate peacefully," Bryza said. "If rallies go to the street then the leaders of those rallies have enormous responsibility in their own han
